Solution Part 1: Adding Buttons and Key Handling

04
On this page
  1. Replacing Inaccessible Elements
    1. The Fullscreen Button
    2. The Next & Previous Buttons
    3. The Dots at the Bottom of the Slideshow
  2. Adding Keyboard Functionality
    1. Exit Fullscreen Mode

The reorderable list demo from the Component Sandbox will serve as the inspiration for some of the slideshow features we’ll implement.

Replacing Inaccessible Elements

The first thing to do is work through slideshow.js and look for div elements that need to become interactive buttons.

The Fullscreen Button

The Enter Fullscreen button was marked up as a div with an onClick event, so it wasn’t reachable by keyboard.

Replace it with the <button> element as well as an ARIA label and optional title:

 <button
  aria-label="Go Full Screen"
  className="btn-slideshow-fullscreen" 
  onClick={enterFullScreen}
  ref={btnFullScreenRef}
  title="Enter Full screen"
>
  <span aria-hidden="true" className="icon"></span>
</button>
 <button
  aria-label="Go Full Screen"
  className="btn-slideshow-fullscreen" 
  onClick={enterFullScreen}
  ref={btnFullScreenRef}
  title="Enter Full screen"
>
  <span aria-hidden="true" className="icon"></span>
</button>

The Next & Previous Buttons

In the existing markup, the arrow icons that navigate between slides used <a> tags with no href but an onClick event. These should be replaced with buttons.

<button
  aria-label="Previous slide"
  className="prev"
  onClick={()=>decrementSlide()}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true">&#10094;</span>
</button>
<button
  aria-label="Next slide"
  className="next"
  onClick={()=>incrementSlide()}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true">&#10095;</span>
</button>
<button
  aria-label="Previous slide"
  className="prev"
  onClick={()=>decrementSlide()}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true">&#10094;</span>
</button>
<button
  aria-label="Next slide"
  className="next"
  onClick={()=>incrementSlide()}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true">&#10095;</span>
</button>

The Dots at the Bottom of the Slideshow

There are dots at the bottom of the slideshow that allow the user to navigate to a particular slide. In the existing markup, the images array is utilized to generate an unordered list with the same number of items.

Here’s the “before” of the dots:

<ul className="dots">
  {images.map((image, index) => (
    <li
      className={`dot ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
      key={index}
      onClick={()=>changeSlide(index)}
    >
    </li>
  ))}
</ul>
<ul className="dots">
  {images.map((image, index) => (
    <li
      className={`dot ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
      key={index}
      onClick={()=>changeSlide(index)}
    >
    </li>
  ))}
</ul>

To refactor this dynamic code, add a button inside of the <li> since list items aren’t interactive.

For ARIA labels for the buttons, use a string template that will interpolate index + 1 as the slide number. This will indicate which image slide the button will target, starting from a 1-based index instead of 0 (more human-friendly!).

The click handler and styling can also move to the button instead of the <li>.

Here’s the “after” markup for the slide show dots:

<ul className="dots">
  {images.map((image, index) => (
    <li key={index}>
      <button
        aria-label={`Go to slide ${index + 1}`}
        className={`dot ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
        onClick={()=>changeSlide(index)}
      >
      </button>
    </li>
  ))}
</ul>
<ul className="dots">
  {images.map((image, index) => (
    <li key={index}>
      <button
        aria-label={`Go to slide ${index + 1}`}
        className={`dot ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
        onClick={()=>changeSlide(index)}
      >
      </button>
    </li>
  ))}
</ul>

Adding Keyboard Functionality

There are multiple opportunities to add keyboard functionality to the slideshow.

Exit Fullscreen Mode

There is a div wrapping the slideshow with a mouse click handler that will exit fullscreen mode:

<div
  className={`inspiration-slideshow ${fullScreenMode ? 'fullscreen' : ''}`}
  onClick={(event)=>handleScreenClick(event)}
>
<div
  className={`inspiration-slideshow ${fullScreenMode ? 'fullscreen' : ''}`}
  onClick={(event)=>handleScreenClick(event)}
>

To add keyboard functionality, below the onClick we can add an onKeyUp event that will pass the event to a keyUpHandler function that we’ll write in a moment. Even though the div itself isn’t focusable or keyboard-interactive, these events will bubble and therefore apply functionality to any focusable elements inside.

Similarly to what we did in a prior lesson, we’ll preemptively add an onKeyDown that will be used for preventing unexpected default behavior when using VoiceOver.

Here’s what the wrapping div looks like now:

<div
  className={`inspiration-slideshow ${fullScreenMode ? 'fullscreen' : ''}`}
  onClick={(event)=>handleScreenClick(event)}
  onKeyDown={preventDefaultFunc}
  onKeyUp={(event)=> { keyUpHandler(event) }}
>
<div
  className={`inspiration-slideshow ${fullScreenMode ? 'fullscreen' : ''}`}
  onClick={(event)=>handleScreenClick(event)}
  onKeyDown={preventDefaultFunc}
  onKeyUp={(event)=> { keyUpHandler(event) }}
>

Outside of the component’s return statement, we’ll write the preventDefaultFunc function. Inside, it will look to see if the user pressed the left or right Arrow keys. If they did, we’ll call event.preventDefault() so VoiceOver will function as we want:

const preventDefaultFunc = (event) => {
  if (event.key === 'ArrowLeft' || event.key === 'ArrowRight') {
    event.preventDefault()
  }
}
const preventDefaultFunc = (event) => {
  if (event.key === 'ArrowLeft' || event.key === 'ArrowRight') {
    event.preventDefault()
  }
}

The keyUpHandler will look to see if the user hit the Escape key or the Arrow keys. If they hit the Escape key, we’ll call closeFullScreen(). If they hit the right Arrow or the down Arrow, we’ll move to the next slide by calling incrementSlide(). Otherwise, if they hit the left or down Arrows, we’ll go back a slide by calling decrementSlide().

Here’s the keyUpHandler code:

const keyUpHandler = (event) => {
  if (event.key === 'Escape') {
    closeFullScreen()
  }
  if (event.key === 'ArrowRight' || event.key === 'ArrowDown') {
    // advance slides
    incrementSlide()
  }
  if (event.key === 'ArrowLeft' || event.key === 'ArrowUp') {
    // reverse slides
    decrementSlide()
  }
}
const keyUpHandler = (event) => {
  if (event.key === 'Escape') {
    closeFullScreen()
  }
  if (event.key === 'ArrowRight' || event.key === 'ArrowDown') {
    // advance slides
    incrementSlide()
  }
  if (event.key === 'ArrowLeft' || event.key === 'ArrowUp') {
    // reverse slides
    decrementSlide()
  }
}
